<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="5" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,914,1660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,914,940]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body moderate to large, TL 
<quantity box="[626,772,914,940]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="6.2" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" unit="mm" value="4.5" valueMax="6.2" valueMin="2.8">2.8–6.2 mm</quantity>
, oblong-oval, slightly convex above; maxillae (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1426,914,940]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,255,937,961]" captionTargetBox="[186,1412,189,892]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[151,1436,176,927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mouthparts of Scirtes luteomaculatus Pic, male. A) mandible, B) maxilla, C) labium." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
) with elongated brush-like galea; labial palpomere 1 as long as palpomere 2 (
<figureCitation box="[1042,1133,954,980]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,255,937,961]" captionTargetBox="[186,1412,189,892]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[151,1436,176,927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mouthparts of Scirtes luteomaculatus Pic, male. A) mandible, B) maxilla, C) labium." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
); mandibles symmetrical, without denticles on mesal edges, pointed at apices (
<figureCitation box="[765,858,994,1020]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,255,937,961]" captionTargetBox="[186,1412,189,892]" captionTargetId="figure-49@5.[151,1436,176,927]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 1. Mouthparts of Scirtes luteomaculatus Pic, male. A) mandible, B) maxilla, C) labium." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
). Setation of abdominal sternites peculiar: sternites III–IV sparsely covered with short setae, setae longer on mesal portion of sternite III and IV, sternite IV with two transverse areas devoided of setation situated close to its anterior margin; sternites V–VII closely covered with long regular setae; caudal margin of sternite VII often shallowly emarginate (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1321,1114,1140]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1680,1704]" captionTargetBox="[180,1410,1074,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-53@5.[171,1416,1066,1640]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Abdominal segments. A) sternites III–VII of Scirtes schawalleroides sp. n., B) tergite VII of Scirtes luteomaculatus Pic." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Tergites I–VII in males lacking apodemes in anterior portion (
<figureCitation box="[781,872,1154,1180]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="5.[151,255,1680,1704]" captionTargetBox="[180,1410,1074,1632]" captionTargetId="figure-53@5.[171,1416,1066,1640]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 2. Abdominal segments. A) sternites III–VII of Scirtes schawalleroides sp. n., B) tergite VII of Scirtes luteomaculatus Pic." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
) (tergite VII in females with apodemes); tergite VIII broad; sternite IX lightly sclerotized; tergite IX almost membranous; tegmen usually symmetrical, Ushaped, with distinct parameres; penis symmetrical, club-like, articulated with tegmen. Sternite VII of females often with a pair of small foveae; prehensor distinct and strongly sclerotized; bursal sclerite indistinct or absent (
<figureCitation box="[242,335,1314,1340]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,255,1432,1456]" captionTargetBox="[180,1408,167,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-166@6.[172,1420,157,1473]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Female genitalia of Scirtes niisatoi sp. n. A) genital tract, B) prehensor, C) sternite VIII, D) tergite VIII." pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,914,1660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
In addition to the above; the elytra often have a colour pattern; the anntenae often with contrasting coloration; basal 3 antennomeres yellow, remaining antennomeres brown to black; the elytral apices in females of some species are modified, with obliquely depressed excitators (sensu 
<bibRefCitation author="Ruta, R." box="[1010,1136,1434,1460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="49 - 68" refId="ref33494" refString="Ruta, R. (2008) Contribution to the knowledge of Seychellois Scirtidae (Coleoptera: Scirtoidea). Zootaxa, 1913, 49 - 68." type="journal article" year="2008">Ruta 2008</bibRefCitation>
) and the females, where known, are often darker than males, either entirely black (
<taxonomicName authority="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta, 2010" authorityName="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta" authorityYear="2010" box="[856,996,1475,1500]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laosensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[856,996,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">S. laosensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1005,1071,1474,1500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta, 2010" authorityName="Yoshitomi &amp; Ruta" authorityYear="2010" box="[1133,1254,1475,1500]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="niisatoi" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1133,1254,1475,1500]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">S. niisatoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1263,1329,1474,1500]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) or with indistinct yellow elytral pattern (spp. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic, F" authorityYear="1935" box="[590,807,1514,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteomaculatus">
cf. 
<emphasis box="[628,807,1515,1540]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">luteomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,914,1660]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,275,1554,1580]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Champion, B" authorityYear="1918" box="[286,530,1555,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Scirtes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavoguttatus">
<emphasis box="[286,530,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Scirtes flavoguttatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group is similar to the 
<emphasis box="[916,1030,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">japonicus</emphasis>
species-group in the oblong-oval shape of the body (
<bibRefCitation author="Nyholm, T." box="[373,541,1594,1620]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="49 - 60" refId="ref33298" refString="Nyholm, T. (2002) Scirtes japonicus Kiesenwetter and its allies, with description of Scirtes ussuriensis n. sp. (Coleoptera, Scirtidae). Entomologische Blatter, 98, 49 - 60." type="journal article" year="2002">Nyholm 2002</bibRefCitation>
), but is distinguished from the latter by the following characteristics: mandibles symmetrical, simply pointed; tegmen U-shaped; penis club-like, articulated with tegmen.
</paragraph>
